english:
  title: Reflections
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Wind and rain persist as they always do,
    spring's cold strikes down the peach and plum trees.
    A wanderer's heart grows hollow and still—
    I sit motionless, sunk in sorrow.

    Quietly the pine winds whisper and roar,
    green mountain mist strikes the paper windows.
    I labor to compose a poem, but fail,
    and mindlessly add more water to my inkstone.

    I have forgotten the affairs of men—
    no grievance troubles me, no joy excites.
    I take children as companions,
    mountain birds as my orchestra.

    Mount Zhongnan rises green above my roof,
    sunlight falls across my reading table.
    Incompetence itself holds a secret flavor—
    at noon I sleep through till evening, unbothered.

    Though I have withdrawn from human affairs,
    my books teem with ancient gentlemen.
    Without reason I smile alone—
    yet cannot explain why.

    Flesh and meat taste sweet, then bitter,
    salt vegetables taste plain, yet savory.
    There was one who gathered ferns on Western Mountain—
    they say he never died.

    I made an old pact with river and lake,
    and morning and evening, I must keep it.
  footnotes:
    - Mount Zhongnan (終南山) is a sacred mountain in classical Chinese poetry, often associated with hermitage and spiritual retreat.
    - The reference to gathering ferns on Western Mountain alludes to the legendary Taoist immortals who rejected worldly affairs and sustained themselves on simple mountain plants, suggesting freedom from mortality through withdrawal from society.
    - The poem's meditation on incompetence and simplicity reflects Daoist philosophy, particularly the virtue of wu-wei (non-action) and the paradoxical fulfillment found in apparent emptiness.
